      "writtenOn": "2020-03-18T17:07:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Each animatable property is always stored as a FooValue (inline in some container).  Additionally, if the property is animated, there\u0027s a FooKeyframeAnimator which stores all the keyframes and points-to/updates the FooValue.\n\nSo for vector properties (currently colors and 3d stuff), we always store a VectorValue long term, and VectorKeyFrameAnimator is optional.\n\nstd::vector\u003cfloat\u003e would work, there\u0027s just a couple of wrinkles which make me hesitate: a) lack of uninitialized allocation (we know we\u0027re going to initialize later, no need to zero-initialize on resize) and b) extra/unneeded semantics take up storage space (e.g. capacity-related internals)\n\nThey\u0027re minor issues though, and come to think of it we resize exactly once per value so it matters even less.\n\nLet\u0027s switch to std::vector and see how it looks.  We can do the same for storage.",
      "parentUuid": "9d06ac49_b9022341",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 43,
        "startChar": 6,
        "endLine": 43,
        "endChar": 17
      },
